heshire, England, United Kingdom":"Beeston, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1342–1401":"1342–1401","1352–Male":"1352–Deceased","1365–1404":"1365–1404","1341–1401":"1341–1401","1370–1420":"1370–1420","1327–1395":"1327–1395","1325–1365":"1325–1365","1341":"1341","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","14 February 1395":"14 February 1395","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Abt 1340":"about 1340","1327":"1327","1404":"1404","1347":"1347","1325":"1325","1401":"1401","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1342":"1342","about 1401":"about 1401","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Beeston,Cheshire,England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Runcorn, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Runcorn, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beeston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from any of the many places in England so called. Those in Nottinghamshire, Norfolk, and Yorkshire were settlements where bent grass grew (Old English <i>bēos</i> ‘rough grass’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’). In Bedfordshire it probably denoted a settlement on a bend (Old English <i>byge</i> + genitive singular <i>-es</i> + <i>tūn</i>). The hamlet stands on a marked bend of the river Yvel. In Cheshire it is named from a rock, below which trading took place (Old English <i>byge</i> ‘commerce’ + Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone’). The reference is to a prominent crag where the remains of Beeston Castle stand. Compare   Beaston   and   Beeson  .","occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived in that part of a village known in Middle English as <i>bi este toun</i> ‘(place) at the east (end) of the village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   and   Beaston  ."]},{"name":"Beeson","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston  , a habitational name from a place called Beeston. The spelling reflects the local pronunciation of the Nottinghamshire placename, although this form is now quite widespread in England."]},{"name":"Beaston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   (the more common form of the surname in England), a habitational name from any of various places called Beeston."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":40,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord William Beeston was born in 1342, in Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Henry de Beeston, was 15 and his mother, Matilda Thornton, was 18. He married Isabel Stoke in 1366, in Beeston, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1401, in his hometown, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1342–1401":"1342–1401","1352–Male":"1352–Surnud","1365–1404":"1365–1404","1341–1401":"1341–1401","1370–1420":"1370–1420","1327–1395":"1327–1395","1325–1365":"1325–1365","1341":"1341","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","14 February 1395":"14. veebruar 1395","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Abt 1340":"umbes 1340","1327":"1327","1404":"1404","1347":"1347","1325":"1325","1401":"1401","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1342":"1342","about 1401":"umbes 1401","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beeston,Cheshire,England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Runcorn, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Runcorn, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Beeston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1342–1401":"1342–1401","1352–Male":"1352–Kuollut","1365–1404":"1365–1404","1341–1401":"1341–1401","1370–1420":"1370–1420","1327–1395":"1327–1395","1325–1365":"1325–1365","1341":"1341","1352":"1352","1395":"1395","14 February 1395":"14. helmikuuta 1395","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Abt 1340":"noin 1340","1327":"1327","1404":"1404","1347":"1347","1325":"1325","1401":"1401","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1342":"1342","about 1401":"noin 1401","of Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Beeston,Cheshire,England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Runcorn, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Runcorn, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Beeston, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1342–1401":"1342–1401","1352–Male":"1352–Décédé","1365–1404":"1365–1404","1341–1401":"1341–1401","1370–1420":"1370–1420","1327–1395":"1327–1395","1325–1365":"1325–1365","1341":"